{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "An introduction to HyperText Markup Language as the standard for creating web pages.",
      "title": "What is HTML?"
    },
    {
      "description": "How HTML provides the structure and content of a web page, separate from its presentation.",
      "title": "The Role of HTML in Web Development"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using HTML tags to describe the meaning and structure of content, not just its appearance.",
      "title": "Semantic HTML"
    },
    {
      "description": "The fundamental structure of every HTML page, including DOCTYPE, html, head, and body.",
      "title": "Anatomy of an HTML Document"
    },
    {
      "description": "The purpose of the `<!DOCTYPE html>` declaration at the beginning of every HTML file.",
      "title": "The DOCTYPE Declaration"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<html>` element as the root container for the entire HTML document.",
      "title": "The Root `<html>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<head>` element's role in containing metadata, such as the page title and links to stylesheets.",
      "title": "The `<head>` Element for Metadata"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<body>` element as the container for all visible content on the web page.",
      "title": "The `<body>` Element for Content"
    },
    {
      "description": "The basic building block of an HTML document, defined by a start tag, content, and an end tag.",
      "title": "What is an HTML Element?"
    },
    {
      "description": "Breaking down an element into its opening tag, the content it contains, and its closing tag.",
      "title": "The Structure of an Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Placing one HTML element inside another to create complex page structures.",
      "title": "Nesting Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements that are self-closing and do not contain any content, like `<br>` or `<img>`.",
      "title": "Empty Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "How to add notes for developers within the HTML code that are not displayed on the page.",
      "title": "HTML Comments"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements that typically start on a new line and take up the full width available.",
      "title": "Block-Level Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "Elements that do not start on a new line and only take up as much width as necessary.",
      "title": "Inline Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "The six levels of heading elements (`<h1>` to `<h6>`) used to structure content by importance.",
      "title": "Heading Elements"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<p>` element used to define a paragraph of text.",
      "title": "The Paragraph Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating hyperlinks to other web pages or resources using the `<a>` element.",
      "title": "The Anchor Element `<a>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating an unordered list with bullet points using the `<ul>` element.",
      "title": "Unordered Lists `<ul>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating an ordered list with numbers or letters using the `<ol>` element.",
      "title": "Ordered Lists `<ol>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<li>` element used to define an item within an ordered or unordered list.",
      "title": "List Items `<li>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<strong>` element for indicating text with strong importance, seriousness, or urgency.",
      "title": "Strong Importance with `<strong>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<em>` element for applying stress emphasis to text, affecting its meaning.",
      "title": "Emphasis with `<em>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<br>` element for inserting a single line break within a block of text.",
      "title": "Line Breaks with `<br>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<hr>` element for creating a thematic break between paragraph-level elements.",
      "title": "Thematic Breaks with `<hr>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using extra name-value pairs within an element's opening tag to configure it or adjust its behavior.",
      "title": "What is an HTML Attribute?"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `id` attribute for providing a unique identifier for a single element on a page.",
      "title": "The `id` Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `class` attribute for applying a common identifier to one or more elements for styling or scripting.",
      "title": "The `class` Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `href` attribute used with the `<a>` element to specify the URL of the page the link goes to.",
      "title": "The `href` Attribute for Links"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `src` attribute used to specify the path to the source file for media elements like `<img>` or `<video>`.",
      "title": "The `src` Attribute for Media"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `alt` attribute for providing alternative text for an image if it cannot be displayed.",
      "title": "The `alt` Attribute for Images"
    },
    {
      "description": "Specifying the dimensions of an image or other media element directly in the HTML.",
      "title": "The `width` and `height` Attributes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Using the `<form>` element as a container for user input controls.",
      "title": "The `<form>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `action` attribute, which specifies the URL where the form data should be sent for processing.",
      "title": "The Form `action` Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `method` attribute, which defines the HTTP method (like GET or POST) to use when submitting the form.",
      "title": "The Form `method` Attribute"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<input>` element, a versatile element for creating various types of form controls.",
      "title": "The `<input>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<label>` element for creating a caption for an item in a user interface.",
      "title": "The `<label>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating a single-line text input field using `<input type=\"text\">`.",
      "title": "Text Input Fields"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating a text input that masks the entered characters using `<input type=\"password\">`.",
      "title": "Password Input Fields"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating a button that submits the form data using `<input type=\"submit\">`.",
      "title": "Submit Buttons"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating radio buttons for selecting one option from a set using `<input type=\"radio\">`.",
      "title": "Radio Buttons"
    },
    {
      "description": "Creating checkboxes for selecting zero or more options from a set using `<input type=\"checkbox\">`.",
      "title": "Checkboxes"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `name` attribute's role in grouping related inputs, such as radio buttons, together.",
      "title": "The `name` Attribute in Inputs"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<textarea>` element for creating a multi-line plain-text editing control.",
      "title": "The `<textarea>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<select>` element for creating a dropdown list of options.",
      "title": "The `<select>` Dropdown Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<option>` element, used inside a `<select>` element to define an item in the list.",
      "title": "The `<option>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding an image into a web page using the `<img>` element.",
      "title": "The `<img>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding a video player into a web page using the `<video>` element.",
      "title": "The `<video>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding a sound file or audio stream into a web page using the `<audio>` element.",
      "title": "The `<audio>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `controls` attribute for adding default play, pause, and volume controls to audio and video elements.",
      "title": "Media Player Controls"
    },
    {
      "description": "Embedding another HTML document, such as a map or YouTube video, into the current page.",
      "title": "Embedding Content with `<iframe>`"
    },
    {
      "description": "The practice of designing web pages so that people with disabilities can use them.",
      "title": "What is Web Accessibility (a11y)?"
    },
    {
      "description": "How using elements for their intended purpose (e.g., `<nav>`, `<button>`) improves accessibility.",
      "title": "Semantic HTML's Role in Accessibility"
    },
    {
      "description": "The critical importance of the `alt` attribute for screen readers to describe images to visually impaired users.",
      "title": "Accessibility of `alt` Text"
    },
    {
      "description": "Associating labels with form inputs to help users of assistive technologies understand the form.",
      "title": "Accessible Form Labels"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<header>` element for introductory content or navigational aids for a page or section.",
      "title": "The `<header>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<footer>` element for a page or section, typically containing authorship, copyright, or contact info.",
      "title": "The `<footer>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<nav>` element for a section of a page that links to other pages or parts within the page.",
      "title": "The `<nav>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<main>` element for the dominant, unique content of the document's body.",
      "title": "The `<main>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<article>` element for self-contained compositions like a forum post, blog entry, or news story.",
      "title": "The `<article>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<section>` element for grouping related content, typically with its own heading.",
      "title": "The `<section>` Element"
    },
    {
      "description": "The `<aside>` element for content that is tangentially related to the main content, like a sidebar.",
      "title": "The `<aside>` Element"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "La fuerza que mantiene unidos a los átomos, iones o moléculas para formar compuestos químicos.",
      "title": "El enlace químico"
    },
    {
      "description": "Los electrones en la capa más externa de un átomo que participan en la formación de enlaces químicos.",
      "title": "Electrones de valencia"
    },
    {
      "description": "La tendencia de los átomos a preferir tener ocho electrones en su capa de valencia para alcanzar la estabilidad.",
      "title": "La regla del octeto"
    },
    {
      "description": "Representación de los electrones de valencia de un átomo usando puntos alrededor de su símbolo químico.",
      "title": "Estructuras de puntos de Lewis para átomos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una medida de la tendencia de un átomo a atraer un par de electrones de un enlace.",
      "title": "Electronegatividad"
    },
    {
      "description": "Atracción electrostática entre iones con cargas opuestas, formados por la transferencia de electrones.",
      "title": "El enlace iónico"
    },
    {
      "description": "La formación de un ion con carga positiva cuando un átomo pierde uno o más electrones.",
      "title": "Formación de cationes"
    },
    {
      "description": "La formación de un ion con carga negativa cuando un átomo gana uno o más electrones.",
      "title": "Formación de aniones"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cómo una gran diferencia de electronegatividad entre dos átomos conduce a un enlace iónico.",
      "title": "Diferencia de electronegatividad en enlaces iónicos"
    },
    {
      "description": "El movimiento completo de electrones de valencia de un átomo a otro.",
      "title": "Transferencia de electrones"
    },
    {
      "description": "El arreglo ordenado y tridimensional de iones en un compuesto iónico.",
      "title": "Redes cristalinas iónicas"
    },
    {
      "description": "Altos puntos de fusión, fragilidad y conductividad eléctrica cuando están disueltos o fundidos.",
      "title": "Propiedades de los compuestos iónicos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un enlace químico que implica la compartición de pares de electrones entre átomos.",
      "title": "El enlace covalente"
    },
    {
      "description": "Compartición equitativa o desigual de electrones para formar moléculas estables.",
      "title": "Compartición de electrones"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace covalente donde se comparte un par de electrones entre dos átomos.",
      "title": "Enlaces covalentes simples"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace covalente donde se comparten dos pares de electrones entre dos átomos.",
      "title": "Enlaces covalentes dobles"
    },
    {
      "description": "Enlace covalente donde se comparten tres pares de electrones entre dos átomos.",
      "title": "Enlaces covalentes triples"
    },
    {
      "description": "Diagramas que muestran el enlace entre átomos de una molécula y los pares solitarios de electrones.",
      "title": "Dibujo de estructuras de Lewis para moléculas"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cuando el átomo central tiene menos de ocho electrones de valencia.",
      "title": "Excepciones al octeto: Octeto incompleto"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cuando el átomo central tiene más de ocho electrones de valencia, posible para elementos del tercer período y posteriores.",
      "title": "Excepciones al octeto: Octeto expandido"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cuando una molécula tiene un número impar de electrones de valencia, resultando en un electrón no apareado.",
      "title": "Excepciones al octeto: Moléculas con electrones impares"
    },
    {
      "description": "La carga asignada a un átomo en una molécula, asumiendo que los electrones en los enlaces se comparten por igual.",
      "title": "Carga formal"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cómo usar la carga formal para determinar la estructura de Lewis más plausible entre varias posibilidades.",
      "title": "Selección de la mejor estructura de Lewis"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cuando una única estructura de Lewis no puede describir adecuadamente el enlace, se utiliza un promedio de múltiples estructuras.",
      "title": "Resonancia"
    },
    {
      "description": "Conjunto de dos o más estructuras de Lewis que contribuyen a la estructura general de una molécula o ion.",
      "title": "Estructuras de resonancia"
    },
    {
      "description": "Distribución desigual de la densidad electrónica en un enlace covalente debido a diferencias de electronegatividad.",
      "title": "Polaridad de enlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un enlace covalente donde los electrones se comparten equitativamente entre dos átomos.",
      "title": "Enlaces covalentes no polares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un enlace covalente donde los electrones se comparten de forma desigual, creando cargas parciales.",
      "title": "Enlaces covalentes polares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una medida de la separación de cargas positivas y negativas en un enlace o molécula.",
      "title": "Momento dipolar"
    },
    {
      "description": "La polaridad general de una molécula, que depende tanto de la polaridad de sus enlaces como de su forma geométrica.",
      "title": "Polaridad molecular"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cómo la disposición simétrica de los enlaces polares puede resultar en una molécula no polar.",
      "title": "Cancelación de dipolos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Modelo para predecir la geometría de moléculas basado en la minimización de la repulsión entre los pares de electrones de la capa de valencia.",
      "title": "Teoría VSEPR"
    },
    {
      "description": "Áreas de densidad electrónica alrededor de un átomo central, que pueden ser enlaces o pares solitarios.",
      "title": "Dominios de electrones"
    },
    {
      "description": "La disposición tridimensional de los dominios de electrones alrededor del átomo central.",
      "title": "Geometría electrónica"
    },
    {
      "description": "La disposición tridimensional de los átomos en una molécula.",
      "title": "Geometría molecular"
    },
    {
      "description": "Geometría para moléculas con dos dominios de electrones alrededor del átomo central (180°).",
      "title": "Geometría lineal"
    },
    {
      "description": "Geometría para moléculas con tres dominios de electrones alrededor del átomo central (120°).",
      "title": "Geometría trigonal plana"
    },
    {
      "description": "Geometría para moléculas con cuatro dominios de electrones alrededor del átomo central (109.5°).",
      "title": "Geometría tetraédrica"
    },
    {
      "description": "Geometría molecular resultante de cuatro dominios electrónicos con un par solitario, como en el amoníaco (NH3).",
      "title": "Geometría piramidal trigonal"
    },
    {
      "description": "Geometría molecular resultante de tres o cuatro dominios electrónicos con pares solitarios, como en el agua (H2O).",
      "title": "Geometría angular"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cómo los pares solitarios ocupan más espacio que los pares enlazantes, reduciendo los ángulos de enlace.",
      "title": "Efecto de los pares solitarios en los ángulos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Describe el enlace químico como el resultado del solapamiento de orbitales atómicos medio llenos.",
      "title": "Teoría del Enlace de Valencia"
    },
    {
      "description": "La mezcla de orbitales atómicos de un átomo para formar nuevos orbitales híbridos para el enlace.",
      "title": "Hibridación de orbitales"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un tipo de enlace covalente formado por el solapamiento frontal de orbitales a lo largo del eje internuclear.",
      "title": "Enlaces sigma (σ)"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un tipo de enlace covalente formado por el solapamiento lateral de orbitales p, por encima y por debajo del eje internuclear.",
      "title": "Enlaces pi (π)"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un orbital s y tres orbitales p para formar cuatro orbitales híbridos con geometría tetraédrica.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp³"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un orbital s y dos orbitales p para formar tres orbitales híbridos con geometría trigonal plana.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp²"
    },
    {
      "description": "Mezcla de un orbital s y un orbital p para formar dos orbitales híbridos con geometría lineal.",
      "title": "Hibridación sp"
    },
    {
      "description": "Hibridación que incluye orbitales d para explicar geometrías como la bipiramidal trigonal y la octaédrica.",
      "title": "Hibridación con orbitales d"
    },
    {
      "description": "Modelo que describe los electrones en una molécula usando orbitales que se extienden sobre toda la molécula.",
      "title": "Teoría de Orbitales Moleculares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Orbitales moleculares de menor energía que los orbitales atómicos originales, que estabilizan la molécula.",
      "title": "Orbitales moleculares de enlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Orbitales moleculares de mayor energía que los orbitales atómicos originales, que desestabilizan la molécula.",
      "title": "Orbitales moleculares de antienlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Representación visual de los niveles de energía de los orbitales moleculares.",
      "title": "Diagramas de orbitales moleculares"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una medida de la fuerza del enlace, calculada como la mitad de la diferencia entre electrones de enlace y antienlace.",
      "title": "Orden de enlace"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cómo la Teoría de Orbitales Moleculares explica la existencia o no de moléculas como H₂ y He₂.",
      "title": "Predicción de la existencia de moléculas"
    },
    {
      "description": "La propiedad de las sustancias que son débilmente atraídas por un campo magnético debido a electrones no apareados.",
      "title": "Paramagnetismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "La propiedad de las sustancias que son débilmente repelidas por un campo magnético porque todos sus electrones están apareados.",
      "title": "Diamagnetismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un tipo de enlace químico entre átomos de metales, caracterizado por electrones deslocalizados.",
      "title": "El enlace metálico"
    },
    {
      "description": "Modelo que visualiza el enlace metálico como una red de cationes metálicos inmersos en un 'mar' de electrones de valencia móviles.",
      "title": "El modelo del mar de electrones"
    },
    {
      "description": "Conductividad eléctrica y térmica, ductilidad, maleabilidad y brillo metálico.",
      "title": "Propiedades de los metales"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Understanding the linear regression model through the lens of vector geometry.",
      "title": "The Geometric View of OLS"
    },
    {
      "description": "Viewing the dependent variable (Y) and each independent variable (X) as vectors in n-dimensional space.",
      "title": "Data as Vectors"
    },
    {
      "description": "The vector subspace spanned by the columns of the regressor matrix X.",
      "title": "The Column Space of Regressors"
    },
    {
      "description": "Interpreting OLS as the orthogonal projection of the outcome vector Y onto the subspace spanned by the regressors X.",
      "title": "Projecting the Outcome Vector"
    },
    {
      "description": "The vector of predicted values, Y-hat, as the result of the projection of Y onto the column space of X.",
      "title": "The Fitted Values Vector (Ŷ)"
    },
    {
      "description": "The vector of estimation errors, e, defined as the difference between the actual outcomes (Y) and the fitted values (Y-hat).",
      "title": "The Residual Vector (e)"
    },
    {
      "description": "The fundamental property that the residual vector is orthogonal (perpendicular) to every regressor vector in X.",
      "title": "Orthogonality of Residuals and Regressors"
    },
    {
      "description": "How OLS finds the coefficient estimates that minimize the sum of squared residuals, which is equivalent to minimizing the length of the residual vector.",
      "title": "Minimizing the Sum of Squared Residuals"
    },
    {
      "description": "The Projection Matrix P, also known as the Hat Matrix, which transforms the Y vector into the fitted values vector Y-hat.",
      "title": "The Projection (Hat) Matrix"
    },
    {
      "description": "Properties of the Projection Matrix, including being symmetric (P' = P) and idempotent (P*P = P).",
      "title": "Properties of the Projection Matrix"
    },
    {
      "description": "The Annihilator Matrix M, which transforms the Y vector into the residual vector e.",
      "title": "The Annihilator (Residual Maker) Matrix"
    },
    {
      "description": "Properties of the Annihilator Matrix, including being symmetric (M' = M) and idempotent (M*M = M).",
      "title": "Properties of the Annihilator Matrix"
    },
    {
      "description": "The model must be a linear function of the parameters, though not necessarily the variables.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 1: Linearity in Parameters"
    },
    {
      "description": "The data represent a random sample drawn from the population, ensuring each observation is independent and identically distributed.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 2: Random Sampling"
    },
    {
      "description": "There are no exact linear relationships among the independent variables. No regressor is a perfect linear combination of others.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 3: No Perfect Collinearity"
    },
    {
      "description": "The issue of high (but not perfect) correlation among independent variables, which can inflate standard errors.",
      "title": "The Problem of Multicollinearity"
    },
    {
      "description": "The error term has an expected value of zero given any values of the independent variables. This is the key exogeneity assumption.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 4: Zero Conditional Mean"
    },
    {
      "description": "The variance of the error term is the same for all observations, regardless of the values of the independent variables.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 5: Homoskedasticity"
    },
    {
      "description": "What happens when the error term variance is not constant across observations.",
      "title": "What is Heteroskedasticity?"
    },
    {
      "description": "The errors for any two different observations are uncorrelated with each other.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 6: No Serial Correlation"
    },
    {
      "description": "What happens when the errors are correlated across observations, common in time-series data.",
      "title": "What is Autocorrelation?"
    },
    {
      "description": "The error term is normally distributed, which is crucial for conducting hypothesis tests in small samples.",
      "title": "CLM Assumption 7: Normality of Errors"
    },
    {
      "description": "The condition that allows for the unique estimation of model parameters from the available data.",
      "title": "What is Parameter Identification?"
    },
    {
      "description": "The requirement that the matrix of regressors, X, must have full column rank to ensure identification.",
      "title": "The Rank Condition for Identification"
    },
    {
      "description": "Why the matrix X'X must be invertible (non-singular) to calculate the OLS estimates.",
      "title": "The Invertibility of X'X"
    },
    {
      "description": "A common example of perfect collinearity that violates the identification condition.",
      "title": "The Dummy Variable Trap"
    },
    {
      "description": "The property that, on average, the estimator will equal the true population parameter.",
      "title": "Properties of Estimators: Unbiasedness"
    },
    {
      "description": "Demonstrating that the expected value of the OLS estimator is the true parameter vector, E(b) = β.",
      "title": "Proving OLS is Unbiased"
    },
    {
      "description": "The spread or dispersion of an estimator's sampling distribution. A lower variance is preferred.",
      "title": "Properties of Estimators: Variance"
    },
    {
      "description": "The property of having the smallest variance among a class of estimators.",
      "title": "Properties of Estimators: Efficiency"
    },
    {
